<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41018c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41018c">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41018c"> 18(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lovefit</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> A sign that he diagnosed a moral not a bodily disorder. We often find in The Nights, the doctor or the old woman distinguishing a <mark>love-fit</mark> by the pulse or similar obscure symptoms, as in the case of Seleucus, Stratonice and her step-son Antiochus which seems to be the arch-type of these anecdotes. <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RBTE3" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE3"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) VII, 174n2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
